<time>1601575670632< /time><Rating>1</Rating>< review>
Since the re-open, their customer service has been very poor..  Some of the fields have not gotten any maintenance in some time..  The heavy set man that runs the place makes you NOT want to come back to US5, little patience, as if he gets bothered very easily  (he pretty much is the motivation behind this post)..  My players and I have been going there for years, always been respectful and courteous, now recently, service is not the same. If they truly want to be successful, they need to make their customers feel appreciated, make them feel as if US5 is their Futbol hub, and right now they are lacking big time, it feels cheap. We are just 1 of a few groups (thus far) that are making the switch to GOALS in south gate (now that they are opening up again).   US5: we root for you, but you need to wake up a.s.a.p or you will lose many more.

Luca<//review>

< text>
We have been playing a lot here, and most of the time local guys who worked there were nice. But yesterday we showed up and it was ABSOLUTELY DISRESPECTFUL and UNPROFESSIONAL situation. It suppose to be a pick up game starting at 6pm every day. We showed up at 8pm and ALL the field were booked. That means that we had to wait for 2 hours to finally start playing (can you imagine on Wednesday when everyone need to go work next day start playing only at 10pm). Anyway with such an unbelievable situation they also asked us to pay which by the way while we were waiting we stayed and spent a lot of money in they local Cafe.

I wouldn't trust 100% to this people over there. Wanna keep coming and play fine, but i would highly recommend to find a new place.< /text>

<userid>113964525608143159852</userid><Name>Tom Tran< /Name><Time>1549258721432<//Time>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
I placed an order via Doordash because it was a group of people from my office munching on here. Ordering wasn't an issue (except there was no option to add extra tuna with a surcharge). Time of pickup wasn't too long.

The only beef I had was the amount of red onion that gets placed into a bowl; one of the bowls requested no red onions because the person eating the bowl was a regular, and she mentioned that the red onions alone can be a side dish. They did mess up the no red onion part, but the server caught it before he gave me my order. (Good thing I didn't request a delivery.)

Eel of Fortune was the choice I went with and I love every bite of it. The sweet crab salad was enough on its own and they didn't skimp on the unagi/avocado ratio at all.

A bit pricey, but what do you expect when you're eating in DTLA?</Text>

<date>1596737257198< /date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
I'd been holding off on taking the COVID test for a while because it seemed like all the healthcare facilities were being overwhelmed and I didn't want to add to the chaos, but with an airline flight coming up at the end of this week, I finally made myself do it.  I researched different places in my area and read a lot of great reviews online for Exer's Pasadena branch, so I decided to give it a try.  There was no appointment needed, which was convenient for me since I had very little time, and once I arrived, I didn't have long to wait before being handed paperwork to fill out as a new patient.  There was only one person in front of me and no one else outside in the waiting area, so there was plenty of space to keep your social distance.  After filling out the paperwork, I was told I could wait in my car and they'd call me, then I drive around back and someone would come to my car to administer the test.  It probably took about 45 minutes to an hour or so in total (even though there were only a few people there), but all the employees were very friendly and took their time to answer my questions.  I got my results in less than a couple days, so the turnaround was lightning fast!  If you need to do a COVID test, I'd highly recommend this place.<//Review>

<Text>This urgent care center calls itself ‚Äúmore than urgent care‚Äù center. It is true. From the time you enter the Center to the time you leave, you will feel that ‚Äúmore than‚Äù claim. It is modern and appears to use the latest state of the art technology. You sign in at a computer station. They have you fill out you personal profile. I waited about 20 minutes then the physician assistant, Christina- a very friendly but professional person, calls me in and takes all vital signs with modern equipment. When she was done, she tells me to wait for bit for the doctor. Within 20 minutes, Dr. Bradley Gerbereich comes in and introduces himself and a scribe. After answering a series of his questions based on what I told Christina, he was able to give me a diagnosis and explained why he arrived at the diagnosis and also explained the medications he was prescribing for me. While the doctor was going through the diagnostics, his scribe was recording it on a tablet computer. The doctor went to get the prescription slips and he returned within a few minutes. And I was out of there without a wait or a hitch.
The only glitch that I encountered was Dr. Gerbereich did not sign the prescription slip but, the Pharmacy was able to call EXER to confirm that it was the doctor‚Äôs prescription and everything was fine.
Definitely, I would recommend EXER highly to anyone.< /Text>< UserId.>

< review>
Under new ownership: this urgent care is NO longer associated with the Huntington Health Physicians/ Huntington Medical Foundation. Unfortunately, nothing online indicates this as of yet. Due to the fact that they are under new ownership I assume that the entire staff is also new and they are terrible.
I took my 5 month old there (on a Saturday) for what I was certain was an ear infection that hadn‚Äôt cleared. This is my 3rd child so I am fairly familiar with what an ear infection looks like in a baby. I was told she did not have an ear infection & that she likely just had a cold that did not require an antibiotic. After 2 more sleepless nights & my baby‚Äôs unnecessary suffering, I took her to her pediatrician first thing Monday morning to be told she did, in fact, still have an ear infection.
The proof here that they missed it & she didn‚Äôt just develop a new one is that the first 1/3 of both of her ears had cleared from the amoxicillin. It was the last 2/3 of both ears that were still infected. Any doctor or nurse practitioner should know to check the whole ear especially in an infant. An ear infection is a simple diagnosis. If you can‚Äôt get that, I don‚Äôt want to know what else you would miss. I am completely disgusted with them. I will not be returning to this Urgent Care again.</review>

<Review>Amazing seafood, fantastic and friendly staff, great atmosphere.

Unsurprisingly, it is expensive.  But you get what you pay for.

The crab is doused in some butter and a little bit of garlic, very tasty albeit messy.  Most people use the excess crab butter to dip the bread in.

The muscles and shrimp come with butter to dip them in.  The shrimp was good, but not nearly as delicious as the muscles.  Very buttery and firm, not fishy or slimy at all.  As someone who has never had muscles before, I highly recommend also trying the muscles (pass on the shrimp).

Very pleased overall.  I'm not a huge fan of cooked seafood, but I really enjoyed this place.  If you are looking for seafood in SF, this is the place to go to.<//Review><rate>5< /rate><GmapID>0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71< /GmapID>< pics>

< Review>
This place is on the West side of the pier, upstairs and at the back. We had great views of the Golden Gate Bridge, and a partial view of Alcatraz. The crab was great, and the two of us were full with the $75 size, with small fries and garlic bread. Did I say small? Yeah, but it is a 10 inch wide bowl. The bread was perfectly toasted. There isn't butter to dip the crab in, but you don't need it since the garlic does the job of keeping it moist and tasty.</Review>

<UserId.>110227997871032016650</UserId.><username>Mar Vy</username>< date>
1519878061525< /date>
< rate>
3</rate>
<text>Intrigued by the World Famous Dungeness Killer Crab and craving for seafood, we decided to have dinner here. We arrived around 8:30 pm, our reservation was set for 9:00 pm.  I thought we had to wait till 9pm but we didn't, they seated us right away.  The restaurant was busy and there were people waiting to be seated.  The ambiance was a little loud.  If you look up towards the ceiling,  you will see decorations of colorful crabs and nets.  We sat by the window so our view was the water and the boat dock.  The waiter took our order, we got shrimps, Dungeness Crab, and clams with fettuccine.

~Drinks~
I took a sip of the Strawberry Mojito, I didn't like it much because it lacked the strawberry flavor.  Instead, I asked for a glass of Riesling (white wine) which tasted better.

~Food~
After ordering,  we were given two loafs of bread.  We used the vinegar and oil to dip the bread in.  The waiter gave us a bib that had a picture of a crab on it.  First, we got the roasted shrimps (12 pieces)  which was served in an iron skillet and it came with a side of warm sauce that tasted like a mixture of butter and lemon. The shrimps were very small; it tasted good with the sauce.  Next was the Dungeness Killer Crab (whole crab - 2 plus pounds) that was roasted in their secret garlic sauce.   I was really looking forward to this dish but I was disappointed because I couldn't taste the garlic. The last one is the Clams with garlic sauce and fettuccine pasta.  The pasta was thick and a little hard but I enjoyed the sauce.

~Customer Service~
They cleared out the plates quickly after we finished our food.  The hostess was nice and friendly.

~Tip~
Call for restaurant reservation

~Notes~
-Crab cracker tool is already placed on the table.< /text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOZ7R4BW0YAmmr_ev1JaqFj7e88wVy_pbSme4U8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMsg8LOSZBBZNSmvuTbQ-T7oHoBb_gTxtSuxdeC=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>< Resp>

<time>1519878061525</time><Rate>3< /Rate>< Review>
Intrigued by the World Famous Dungeness Killer Crab and craving for seafood, we decided to have dinner here. We arrived around 8:30 pm, our reservation was set for 9:00 pm.  I thought we had to wait till 9pm but we didn't, they seated us right away.  The restaurant was busy and there were people waiting to be seated.  The ambiance was a little loud.  If you look up towards the ceiling,  you will see decorations of colorful crabs and nets.  We sat by the window so our view was the water and the boat dock.  The waiter took our order, we got shrimps, Dungeness Crab, and clams with fettuccine.

~Drinks~
I took a sip of the Strawberry Mojito, I didn't like it much because it lacked the strawberry flavor.  Instead, I asked for a glass of Riesling (white wine) which tasted better.

~Food~
After ordering,  we were given two loafs of bread.  We used the vinegar and oil to dip the bread in.  The waiter gave us a bib that had a picture of a crab on it.  First, we got the roasted shrimps (12 pieces)  which was served in an iron skillet and it came with a side of warm sauce that tasted like a mixture of butter and lemon. The shrimps were very small; it tasted good with the sauce.  Next was the Dungeness Killer Crab (whole crab - 2 plus pounds) that was roasted in their secret garlic sauce.   I was really looking forward to this dish but I was disappointed because I couldn't taste the garlic. The last one is the Clams with garlic sauce and fettuccine pasta.  The pasta was thick and a little hard but I enjoyed the sauce.

~Customer Service~
They cleared out the plates quickly after we finished our food.  The hostess was nice and friendly.

~Tip~
Call for restaurant reservation

~Notes~
-Crab cracker tool is already placed on the table.< /Review>

< Review>
My experience was just okay.

I didn't get served for about 10 minutes after being shown to my table, not even a hello or offering drinks. I did not receive service until I asked for it.
I don't really factor that into this review though, food is the important part.

I had the crab chowder in a sourdough bowl, and I would say it was average.
Temperature was perfect, however other things were not.
For a chowder, it was incredibly thin, lacking the thickness you would expect from a good chowder. I would say it was closer to a soup than a chowder.
Flavour wise, unfortunately it was lacking. While it had many ingredients, none of these flavours really stood out or were very obvious. Nearly flavourless. For a seafood chowder, you would expect more of an ocean flavour, however, that was not present here.
Presentation was great, as you can see.

Overall, for 15 dollars, you are likely better served getting chowder from elsewhere.
Unfortunate, because the view of the bay from the restaurant is excellent.<//Review>

< text>
This place is on the West side of the pier, upstairs and at the back. We had great views of the Golden Gate Bridge, and a partial view of Alcatraz. The crab was great, and the two of us were full with the $75 size, with small fries and garlic bread. Did I say small? Yeah, but it is a 10 inch wide bowl. The bread was perfectly toasted. There isn't butter to dip the crab in, but you don't need it since the garlic does the job of keeping it moist and tasty.</text>

<Time>1558171103076< /Time><rating>4< /rating><Gmap_id>0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71</Gmap_id><name>Joanna Ball</name></record></dataset><record>

110905922640836032678</userid>
<name>Wesley Redmond<//name>< time>
1554414339180<//time>
<Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
My experience was just okay.

I didn't get served for about 10 minutes after being shown to my table, not even a hello or offering drinks. I did not receive service until I asked for it.
I don't really factor that into this review though, food is the important part.

I had the crab chowder in a sourdough bowl, and I would say it was average.
Temperature was perfect, however other things were not.
For a chowder, it was incredibly thin, lacking the thickness you would expect from a good chowder. I would say it was closer to a soup than a chowder.
Flavour wise, unfortunately it was lacking. While it had many ingredients, none of these flavours really stood out or were very obvious. Nearly flavourless. For a seafood chowder, you would expect more of an ocean flavour, however, that was not present here.
Presentation was great, as you can see.

Overall, for 15 dollars, you are likely better served getting chowder from elsewhere.
Unfortunate, because the view of the bay from the restaurant is excellent.<//text>

< review>
Went here with family, as we have always wanted to try the place out.  Sadly we're never going back.

The place wasn't busy.  Never asked us how the meal was, never refilled our drinks without us asking.

Bruschetta was soggy... Half a crab was just four small legs.... The shrimp cocktail was just shrimp on a stick with cocktail sauce on the side.... My God what was the crab cocktail then!?!   The pasta was the best dish  however it was still over cooked.

This place probably started as an awesome Italian place, and our guess is they sold the business long ago to people who don't know how to cook Italian but kept the menu the same.   Shameful really.  Any other place on Pier 39 is better than here.</review>

<username>Vicente Trevino<//username>< time>
1466385757254< /time>
< rating>
2</rating>
< Review>
To start, it is San Francisco and its very busy. Still, from the moment you walk in, its rushed, chaotic and impossible to walk without bumping into anything.

To many tables in a very tight places makes eating any meal not very enjoyable. Maybe the concentration should be less tables and better customer experience rather than what felt like the, "burn and turn" system. Staff is friendly, but you really cant blame them. They can only work with what they have.

The food was average, the price not so.

The Crab Pot in Pikes Market in Seattle, does a much better job of providing a dine by the pier experience. Where the food is much more  worth the price on the menu.

Fastest  $75 buck lunch ever. Not to mention I still picked up something to eat 10 minutes after walking on the pier.

You live and you learn. Hope this helps someone else.</Review>

I made a reservation here by using Open Table and got right in easily while there was a line on a Saturday. The restaurant is extremely tight and even more so when they place you at a booth along the walkway of the waiters going to the kitchen. The tables at the booths are very small and then they give you very long plates. It doesn‚Äôt make sense. I ordered a tea and the Waite brings me a coke. I never order sodas so I‚Äôm pretty sure I didn‚Äôt misspeak. When I asked for a tea instead, he looked confused and asked if I still wanted it. I said no so he brought out the tea and left the coke in the table. I ordered a crab melt, my friend ordered fried fish and her husband ordered crab legs. My melt was so full of onions that I had a pile of them sitting on the side. There wasn‚Äôt that much crab meat but tons of cheese. It was more like a grilled cheese sandwich with some crab. My friend ate her fish and began feeling sick. Her husband ate his crab and said he never tasted much of a flavor. There was nothing special to the legs to set them apart from a mom and pop place somewhere else. We got in the car and my friend felt even worse. Once she got home, she threw up her fish. Not sure what was going on but from how tight the restaurant is, the bad decision to use long plates for small tables, tasteless crab, piles of onions, and bad fish, we won‚Äôt be back.< /review>

The Crab House is located on the 2nd level on the right. We dined here for lunch, it was very crowded. We waited about 25 minutes.

My wife and I ordered the pasta dishes with crab, we didn't feel like getting our hands messy trying to get the crab meat out if the shells.

Both dishes was filled with large pieces of crab meat. The sauce was creamy and full of flavour.

The service was quick. Some of the staff were friendly and helpful and some were not.

Also, they do validate parking if you're parked directly across the street in the 5 level garage. But make sure they do it. I gave our waiter our parking ticket but when we paid , it wasn't validated! It's $10/ hr.</Text>

<Review>I have not written a review before, but I was compelled to share this ridiculously rude and disappointing experience with The Crab House management. Our group of 42 found our ideal restaurant choice in the Fisherman‚Äôs Wharf area. I worked with Cody, Manager (seemingly very helpful), to create a fixed $50 banquet menu, shared our RSVP headcount, and submitted the required written banquet reservation form 7 days prior to our group event, guaranteed with my credit card.  Cody emailed 7 days prior, ‚ÄúPerfect, I have everything I need. Look forward to seeing you next Saturday.‚Äù

Less than 24 hours before our reservation, on the way to our airport flight to SF, he calls to inform us that The Crab House unfortunately cannot honor the reservation due to capacity challenges (we would occupy 1/3 of the space on a Saturday afternoon).  Are you effing kidding???  What type of restaurant would ethically do this?  We already had an off peak hour reservation at 4:30, so I offered to shorten our meal duration from 120 minutes to 90 minutes and move it up to 4pm.  Or break us up into 3 groups for seating. They remained faintly apologetic but inflexible, only offering us walk-in status, not even on the reservation slate.  Nor did he offer to make any effort to arrange substitute reservations at their sister restaurants and placed blame upon being uninformed of the restaurant owner‚Äôs ‚Äúnew policy.‚Äù They were obviously not willing to make exceptions through this policy to serve willing patrons through the transition.

Our group of families ended up having a fast food dinner at the Ferry Building. Embarrassed by this disastrous dining situation, I would absolutely not recommend The Crab House to anyone and will encourage our group to anti-crusade against this and their associated establishments. Their level of unaccommodating, non-service to prospective patrons is absurd, shameful, and unjustifiable.  Hopefully others seeking to have a moderately sized group dinner here will be dissuaded from wasting time arranging an event, at risk for breach of contract or other dubious practices.< /Review>< gmap_id>
0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71< /gmap_id>

<pictures>None<//pictures><Review>The food was delicious, service was great and the views were spectacular. It was fun to watch the bartender turn out drinks like a machine and the staff working together to provide quick, friendly service. I love crab and was really excited about the menu. The reason for 4 stars instead of 5 is because it was pretty pricey not to come with any sides, salad, bread, etc., the chowder was luke warm and could've used a bit more flavor, and I would've liked to have some lemon and plain drawn butter for my crab but I was too embarrassed to ask since it's cooked with butter and garlic. <rating>4<//rating>< Review>
We visited the Crab House on a Saturday night at 9:00pm, for a birthday dinner.  We had reservations so there was no wait and we were seated immediately. The dress is casual and the atmosphere is lively, so don‚Äôt expect dim lights with candlelight and white tablecloths. For the 4 of us we ordered the Too Two Crab and it was enough for all of us. The crab and marinade was absolutely delicious! I salivate just thinking about it.  We also ordered the large size garlic fries. The fries were well seasoned and very good but I would recommend getting the medium serving instead because the large is enormous and there was so much left over.  We did have one problem when paying for our bill. Our credit card was not returned after paying. When my husband hunted down the waitress, she had originally charged our bill and erroneously charged the table next to us on our credit card.  The problem was quickly rectified, but I wonder if we would have lost our credit card if my husband had not realized it was missing. Another thing that bothered my husband, that while he was signing for the credit card charge, the waitress stood right over him while calculating the tip. We felt that was highly inappropriate.  The error was unfortunate, but the crab tasted so amazing, we still will be returning.< /Review>

< user_id>
106948099488847378474</user_id>
< user_name>
Brad Seehawer<//user_name>
<date>1272504175993</date>< Rating>
4< /Rating>
<text>Even though I'm not from the city, it's pretty obvious that you shouldn't go to the city's biggest tourist attraction for a good meal. The multitude of positive reviews on Yelp made me take a chance on Crab House.

The place is sort of out of the way on the pier, and they were happy to accommodate my reservation for eight later that night. Service was extraordinarily quick throughout the night, with single-digit minutes transpiring between placing orders and receiving our food, though I would think that a place called Crab House would have plenty of crab ready to go.

We started with two orders of garlic fries for the table, and the serving size was plenty large enough for everyone to have a share. The fries were only so-so, but the big blast of garlic no small consolation.

I grabbed a bowl of crab chowder, too. I thought the proportion of vegetables (carrot, corn, and potato) were almost too much for the small cup of chowder, preventing the crab (what should have been the star) to shine through.

The giant 6.5 lbs platter of crab we ordered was listed as serving four on the menu, but it fed five well. The garlic butter provided good coverage, though I could have appreciated a side of said butter for dipping. The cast iron griddle on which it was served was so hot that it provided a rich flavor to the meat.

As I walked past one of the many chain seafood restaurants on the Wharf, I wondered if they used fresh seafood or worked from the same suppliers as the rest of their locations in other parts of the country. I wasn't about to find out. You can do a whole lot worse on the Wharf, and - though a little expensive - Crab House lives up to its name.< /text>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Response>
None< /Response>

< userid>
105298808051772975330</userid>
< name>
Travis A</name>
<Time>1505281860559< /Time><Rate>4< /Rate>< review>
The food was delicious! The atmosphere was "okay"; for that price it needs to looks a little more stylish, or at least intentional. It just didn't have that 25 dollar plate appeal, you know? Speaking of the appearance, the unisex bathroom was pretty gross. The waiter was "okay" - he was nice, but he forgot my water (table of 3) and he also seemed to have abandoned us for a while.
Also. THE CRAB CAKES ARE WAY TOO SMALL for the price they are. I never mind spending more than usual when it comes to seafood, but crab cakes that are the size of a half dollar is just a sad thing.  - This is especially disappointing when it costs 38 half dollars to buy them...
But again. The food and even the tiny crab cakes is very tasty, and the light sauce that they come on top of is DELICIOUS.
all in all the food is good , if I haven't mentioned that,  and although it's not the cleanest place it is a classic. You definitely want to eat here if you can afford it.

Okay another thing to note because I'm looking at their menu now that I'm home: WHY DO THEY INCLUDE "AN ADDITIONAL 4.9% TO ALL CHECKS to OFFSET THE COSTS OF DOING BUSINESS AND GOVERNMENT MANDATED EXPENSES"???  - - - One's cost of doing business is their cost of doing business. Not mine.. How does that even make sense?? - You pay for your cost of doing business with the business that you do. *Meaning, you prepare and sell food and serve alcohol. ...If you aren't covering business expenses with what you're doing, than you are failing. Literally failing what it means to be a profitable business... $46 per crab and you can't cover the cost of doing business without adding on an extra 4.9% to someone's total bill? Comical. I don't even understand lol. - A party of 5 can easily spend $200. And you can't afford the cost of doing business without extra assistance?   Dude... I don't know. That's embarrassing to put out there. Add a dollar to the cost of each  menu, and cover your cost that way, if you have to. Lol. I can't believe I just saw that.

< Date>
1431581265442</Date>
< text>
Came here for a double birthday party. Really pricey for what was being served. Definitely geared to tourists.  We ordered two Killer Crab Feasts (4 servings or 2 medium sized Dungeness Crabs per Feast) with secret garlic sauce (which didn't have much of a garlic taste).

Steamed Mussels, Caesar Salad. Bruschetta. All average tasting. Garlic Noodles (that didn't have much garlic flavor). Service was slow. The Pineapple Mojitos were weak (for $11.95/glass I expect some alcohol).

The place was crowded with tourists and the wait was long for them. On the plus side, the view was nice. Crab House let us bring in our two birthday cakes for us to serve and did not charge a cake cutting fee. They validate parking for 1 hr during lunch and 2 hrs during dinner hours.

We came for lunch and even with 1 hr validation parking with still $18. Again, for what we ate and what this place charges for crab, not worth going back. There are many other places in San Francisco that serves Dungeness crab in garlic sauce that are better tasting, cost less and don't have to pay such an outrageous price to park.</text>

None</Pictures>
